# CLI Message Styling: Minimal Emphasis

When writing user-facing CLI messages (status prompts, error messages, confirmations, progress updates), follow these rules to keep emphasis minimal and purposeful.

## Core Principle

Bold and color should highlight **only the minimal core phrase** — the result or status. Everything else (complements, hints, IDs, details) stays in default or dimmed style.

## Standard Formatters (use these!)

Always use the reusable functions from `logic/turing/status.py` instead of hand-assembling ANSI strings:

```python
from interface.status import fmt_status, fmt_detail, fmt_stage, fmt_warning, fmt_info

print(fmt_status("Saved.", dim="3 policies"))          # bold label + dim detail
print(fmt_status("Failed.", complement="Try /setup.", style="error"))
print(fmt_detail("Session be58ac60 is ready."))        # auto-dimmed, 4-space indent
print(fmt_stage("Starting...", status="active"))       # > indicator with bold label
print(fmt_warning("Using cached results."))            # Warning: ... (dimmed)
print(fmt_info("Session ID: be58ac60"))                # dimmed info line
```

These enforce indent, truncation, and the minimal-emphasis rule automatically.

For Turing machine stages, `ProgressTuringMachine` also provides:
- `pm.warning("text")` — emit a dimmed warning via the display manager
- `pm.info("text")` — emit a dimmed info line via the display manager

## Grammatical Structure

Status messages follow one of these patterns:

| Pattern | Bold Part | Default/Dim Part |
|---------|-----------|-----------------|
| Verb + Noun | **Saved.** | |
| Verb + Adjective | **Session not found.** | `be58ac60` |
| Adverb + Verb | **Successfully saved.** | |
| Noun + Verb | **Provider not configured.** | Run /setup to configure. |

The bold portion forms the **minimal complete predicate** — the shortest phrase that conveys the outcome. Everything after it is a complement (explanation, hint, ID, path) and should not be bold.

## Examples

```python
from interface.status import fmt_status, fmt_detail

# CORRECT: use fmt_status — enforces bold label + default/dim rest
print(fmt_status("Deleted.", dim=session_id))
print(fmt_status("Session not found.", dim=sid))
print(fmt_status("Provider not configured.", complement="Run /setup to configure."))
print(fmt_status("Unknown command.", complement="Type /help.", style="error"))

# ALSO CORRECT: manual ANSI when fmt_status doesn't fit
print(f"  {BOLD}Deleted.{RESET} {DIM}{session_id}{RESET}")

# WRONG: bolding the entire message including complements
print(f"  {BOLD}Deleted session {session_id}.{RESET}")
print(f"  {BOLD}Session not found: {sid}{RESET}")
print(f"  {BOLD}Provider not configured. Run /setup to configure.{RESET}")
```

## Color Usage

| Element | Style |
|---------|-------|
| Status result (success) | `{BOLD}text{RESET}` or `{GREEN}{BOLD}text{RESET}` |
| Status result (error) | `{RED}{BOLD}text{RESET}` |
| Complement / hint | Default style (no formatting) |
| IDs, paths, details | `{DIM}text{RESET}` |
| Stage indicator `>` | Colored by state (green=done, red=error, default=active) |
| Stage label | `{BOLD}label{RESET}` (may include color, e.g. `{GREEN}{BOLD}`) |
| Stage description | Default style |
| Detail lines | `{DIM}text{RESET}` (auto-applied by `fmt_detail()`) |
| Warning notices | `{YELLOW}{DIM}Warning:{RESET} {DIM}text{RESET}` (use `fmt_warning()`) |
| Info notices | `{DIM}text{RESET}` (use `fmt_info()`) |

## Punctuation

- In-progress messages end with `...` (e.g., "Starting session...")
- Completed/reference states end with `.` (e.g., "Session started.")
- Never use `!` in status messages.

## Structured Stage Display

Agent operations use the `> label desc` format:

```
  > {BOLD}Preparing request{RESET} Sending to zhipu-glm-4-flash (step 1)... [logs/s1.log.md]
    {DIM}ID: be58ac60-1234-5678-abcd{RESET}
```

The `>` indicator is colored by state; the label is always bold; the description and details are never bold.
